    "instruction": "Using the full log.csv, compute the global P95 for each (cmdb_id, log_name) pair across the entire series and store these thresholds. Then filter log.csv to the incident window 2024-01-25 00:25:30 UTC to 2024-01-25 00:55:30 UTC (inclusive) and restrict to cmdb_id in [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\"]. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (value >= global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC datetime of first anomalous point), max_value_in_window, and global_p95. Return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95 — limit to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count descending. Store the filtered windowed log dataframe as 'logs_window' and the summary as 'log_anomaly_summary_window' but only print the requested compact summary. Additionally, filter error_logs.csv to the same incident window and candidate services and return up to the first 20 rows with columns timestamp (UTC), cmdb_id, and message, sorted by timestamp; store this filtered table as 'error_logs_window'."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and anomaly detection for metrics, traces, and logs. Summary so far: metrics narrow suspects to three service-level components (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service) showing brief spikes in CPU/memory/socket/latency and short bursts in log.row_count around 00:28–00:36 UTC. Trace-based anomaly signals were degenerate (error_rate p95 = 0) and uninformative. No raw error log messages were found in error_logs.csv for these services in the incident window. According to the workflow, with multiple service-level candidates we must localize the root cause using traces to identify call chains and determine the most downstream faulty service. Even though error_rate traces were degenerate, trace naming and duration metrics may still reveal which candidate is downstream and whether any duration/latency spans for those services are elevated in the incident window. Therefore the next step is to inspect trace relationships and per-trace duration/latency stats within the incident window to see which of the metric-flagged services is downstream in call chains and whether any trace durations/latencies are elevated around the spike times (00:28–00:36 UTC).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full trace.csv and the incident window 2024-01-25 00:25:30 UTC to 2024-01-25 00:55:30 UTC (inclusive), restrict attention to traces whose cmdb_id is one of: [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"]. From these traces, produce a compact table of distinct trace_name values (max 50 rows) where trace_name contains any of these substrings: 'to_ts-auth-service','from_ts-auth-service','to_ts-order-service','from_ts-order-service','to_ts-route-service','from_ts-route-service','to_ts-travel-service','from_ts-travel-service','duration','duration_mean','duration_p95','latency'. For each returned trace_name compute: total_points_in_window, mean_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, and earliest_timestamp_in_window. Sort the table by total_points_in_window descending and limit to 50 rows. Also separately return a small list (up to 20 entries) of unique trace_name values within the window that explicitly mention calls between the candidate services (i.e., trace_name strings that contain any of the other candidate service names), so we can infer call directions among the candidates. Store the filtered results as 'candidate_trace_window' and the summary as 'candidate_trace_summary' in kernel variables but only print the requested compact summaries."
}

{
    "analysis": "So far we followed the prescribed workflow: computed global thresholds over full series, filtered to the incident window, ran metric analysis (which flagged short spikes across ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service), ran trace analysis (trace error_rate series were degenerate with p95=0 and uninformative, but duration/row_count traces show a common earliest anomaly around 2024-01-25 00:28:00 UTC and large row_count spikes toward ts-route-service), and ran log analysis (log.row_count spikes for the same services around 00:29–00:36 UTC; no raw error messages in error_logs). The metrics and logs indicate a traffic surge and short resource spikes across auth, order, and route; traces show large row_count and some elevated root duration_p95 (tail up to ~1.0s) with earliest timestamp 00:28:00. According to the localization rules, when multiple service-level components are faulty we should pick the most downstream faulty service in the trace call chain. The evidence so far suggests heavy inbound traffic/row_count toward ts-route-service at 00:28 and elevated root-level tail latency at the same time; however we have not yet confirmed which service's trace durations (duration_mean / duration_p95 / latency) exceed their global thresholds in the incident window. To decide the root-cause service/component and failure reason we need one more compact trace-duration anomaly pass restricted to duration/latency trace features for the candidate services to identify which service shows true duration anomalies (not just error_rate artifacts) and whether those occur downstream in the call chain around 00:28–00:36 UTC.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For cmdb_id in [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] find all trace_name values that contain any of these substrings: 'duration', 'duration_mean', 'duration_p95', or 'latency'. For each matching (cmdb_id, trace_name):\n1) Compute the global P95 over the full trace.csv series (store as global_p95).\n2) Filter trace rows to the incident window 2024-01-25 00:25:30 UTC through 2024-01-25 00:55:30 UTC (inclusive).\n3) For the rows in the window compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (value >= global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC of first value >= global_p95, or NaN if none), max_value_in_window, mean_value_in_window, and global_p95.\nReturn a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95 — limit to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count descending. Store the filtered windowed traces as 'trace_duration_window' and the summary as 'trace_duration_anomaly_summary' but only print the requested compact summary."
}

Based on the telemetry analysis (metrics, traces, logs) in the incident window, the most likely root cause is a transient resource-pressure event on ts-auth-service that produced root-span tail latency and brief downstream impact around 2024-01-25 00:28:00 UTC. The best-matching reason from the provided list is high CPU usage.

